<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910320-0058</DOCNO><DOCID>910320-0058.</DOCID><HL>   Grafton Says Payment   Of Dividends Depends   On Banks' Consent</HL><DATE>03/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T.GFG</CO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)DIVIDENDS (DIV)</IN><LP>   TORONTO -- Grafton Group Ltd. said that under an agreementwith its banks, the retailing company and its subsidiarieswon't be permitted to pay dividends without the banks'consent.   Grafton didn't further describe the agreement, which itsaid was to be signed today. The company said in January thatit and a group of Canadian banks planned to replace andconsolidate loans that had been made separately to Graftonand its subsidiaries.</LP><TEXT>   Grafton said that because of the agreement its Maher Inc.subsidiary, a footwear chain, won't declare the quarterlydividend that would have been payable April 1 on Maher'spreferred shares. As previously reported, Grafton decidedlast month not to declare a quarterly dividend on its ownSeries A preferred shares.   Grafton previously said that the bankruptcy of 66%-ownedElks Inc., a clothing retailer, would cause it to record acharge of 10 million Canadian dollars (US$8.7 million) in thefiscal year ended Jan. 31. In the first nine months, theparent company reported a C$17.4 million loss on sales ofC$385.1 million.</TEXT></DOC>